The issue you&#39;re encountering is due to the way you structured your code. The `hasNextDouble()` and `nextDouble()` methods of the Scanner class should be used together to ensure proper input reading. In your current code, you&#39;re calling `in.nextDouble()` multiple times without re-prompting the user for input.

```
import java.util.Scanner;

public class CountDownByTwos {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        double num = 0; // Initialize num
        
        // Get a valid positive number from the user
        while (true) {
            System.out.println(&quot;Input a positive number and I will count down by 2&quot;);
            
            if (in.hasNextDouble()) {
                num = in.nextDouble();
                if (num &gt;= 0) {
                    break; // Break the loop if a valid positive number is provided
                } else {
                    System.err.println(&quot;Please input a POSITIVE number&quot;);
                }
            } else {
                String input = in.next();
                System.err.println(input + &quot; is not a number, try again please&quot;);
            }
        }
        
        // Use a for loop to count down by 2 until it reaches 0
        for (double i = num; i &gt;= 0; i -= 2) {
            System.out.println(i);
        }
    }
}

```

In this code:

1. We initialize `num` to `0` outside the loop to ensure it&#39;s defined before being used.

2. We use a `while` loop to repeatedly prompt the user for input until a valid positive number is provided.

3. Inside the loop, we use `hasNextDouble()` to check if the next input is a double. If it is, we then check if it&#39;s greater than or equal to `0`. If both conditions are met, we break out of the loop. If not, we display an error message.

4. If the input is not a valid double, we display an error message and continue the loop.

5. Once a valid positive number is obtained, we use a `for` loop to count down by 2 until it reaches `0`.

